bib.title: Effect of projectile structure in incomplete fusion in 24Mg + 59Co reaction

free_txt: Pelletron Accelerator at TIFR, Colaba,
Mumbai,India (14 MV Tandem accelerator)
Compiled by Dr. Sarbjit Singh, B.A.R.C.,
Mumbai, India. Varinderjit Singh, Punjab University,
Chandigarh and P.M. Prajapati MSU,Baroda helped for
the data input.
Energy spectra of PLFs were integrated to
obtain the lab angular distribution of PLFs. In the
energy spectra of C, a low-energy component was
observed due to the 24-Mg + 16-O reaction, which was
not included in the integration. Lab angular
distributions of PLFs were transformed into a centre-
of-mass (CM) frame using the CM kinetic energies of
PLFs.
Cross-sections for projectile-like fragments (PLFs)
have been measured in the 24-Mg + 59-Co reaction at
lab Energy = 93, 100 and 108 MeV to investigate the
projectile structure effect in incomplete fusion (ICF)
reactions. In this study, the cross-sections for ICF
channels involving the emission of Ne, O and C were
found to be higher than the other ICF
channels involving the emission of odd Z PLFs. This
observation was attributed to the alpha cluster
structure of the 24-Mg nucleus. Significant
cross-sections for incomplete fusion reactions at
these beam energies indicated that the
collision trajectories with l < l (crit) are
contributing to ICF.
Silicon E-dE telescopes, 20 and
1000 mu-m. The lab. angular distributions were
measured in the angular range of 12.- 35.degr.
Two monitor detectors were kept at +-10.degr. to
monitor the elastically scattered beam. The data of the
monitor detectors was used to normalize the count
rates in the telescopes for the beam current and the
target thickness to determine the differential
cross-sections for PLFs.
Uncertainties on the cross-section are due
to the extrapolation of the measured angular
distribution.
